  "eprint": {
    "title": "Direct Sum Masking as a Countermeasure to Side-Channel and Fault Injection Attacks",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Claude Carlet",
        "email": "guilley@secure-ic",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Sylvain Guilley",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Sihem Mesnager",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Internet of Things is developing at a very fast rate. In order to ensure security and privacy, end-devices (e.g. smartphones, smart sensors, or any connected smartcards) shall be protected both against cyber attacks (coming down from the network) and against physical attacks (arising from attacker low-level interaction with the device).\nIn this context, proactive protections shall be put in place to mitigate information theft from either side-channel monitoring or active computation/data corruption.\nAlthough both countermeasures have been developing fast and have become mature,\nthere has surprisingly been little research to combine both.\n\nIn this article, we tackle this difficult topic and highlight a viable solution.\nIt is shown to be more efficient than mere fault detection by repetition (which is anyway prone to repeated correlated faults).\nThe presented solution leverages the fact that both side-channel protection and fault attack detection are coding techniques.\nWe explain how to both prevent (higher-order) side-channel analyses and\ndetect (higher-order) fault injection attacks.\nThe specificity of this method is that it works ``end-to-end'', meaning that the detection can be delayed until the computation is finished.\nThis simplifies considerably the error management logic as there is a single verification throughout the computation.",
    "keywords": [
      "Security",
      "privacy",
      "Internet of Things",
      "side-channel analysis",
      "fault injection attacks",
      "countermeasure",
      "high-order",
      "coding theory",
      "direct sum masking (DSM)"
    ],
    "category": "Implementation",
